  "prompt": "Why is sodium hydrogen carbonate soluble in water?",
  "response": "Sodium hydrogen carbonate (NaHCO\u2083), commonly known as baking soda, is soluble in water due to its ionic nature and the interactions between its ions and water molecules. Here\u2019s why it dissolves:\n\n1. **Ionic Nature**: Sodium hydrogen carbonate is an ionic compound, consisting of sodium ions (Na\u207a) and bicarbonate ions (HCO\u2083\u207b). Ionic compounds tend to dissolve in polar solvents like water because the polar water molecules can effectively separate the ions from the crystal lattice.\n\n2. **Polarity of Water**: Water is a polar molecule with a partial positive charge on the hydrogen atoms and a partial negative charge on the oxygen atom. This polarity allows water molecules to surround and interact with the Na\u207a ions (through the oxygen atoms in water) and the HCO\u2083\u207b ions (through the hydrogen atoms in water).\n\n3. **Hydration**: When sodium hydrogen carbonate dissolves in water, the Na\u207a and HCO\u2083\u207b ions become hydrated. This means they are surrounded by water molecules, which stabilizes them in solution. The energy released during hydration (hydration energy) helps overcome the lattice energy holding the ions together in the solid state.\n\n4. **Solubility Equilibrium**: While sodium hydrogen carbonate is soluble, its solubility is limited compared to other salts like sodium chloride (NaCl). This is because the HCO\u2083\u207b ion can participate in further chemical reactions (like dissociation or hydrolysis) that can affect its solubility. However, under normal conditions, it readily dissolves in water.\n\nIn summary, sodium hydrogen carbonate dissolves in water due to the strong electrostatic interactions between its ions and the polar water molecules, combined with the favorable hydration of the ions.",
